03612nmm a2200517Ia 9781438437477DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814384374777 a10.1515/97814384374772doi  a(DE-B1597)683063  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0180002bisacsh04a115qOCoLC222/eng/202311201 aPerone, Ugo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Possible Present /cUgo Perone. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (150 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSUNY series in Contemporary Italian Philosophy0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Possible Present unfolds from within a freely reinterpreted hermeneutic perspective and provides an original theoretical proposal on the topic of time. In dialogue especially with the philosophies of Husserl and Heidegger, but resorting also to suggestions coming from a theological background (Barth and Bonhoeffer), the work proposes a personal and original theory of time centered on a conception of the present that does not reduce temporality to a succession of mere instants. When one claims that time is ungraspable, one refers neither to the past (which is rather irretrievable) nor to the future (which is rather uncertain) but to the present. The present in which we are is in fact what fades from our hands without break. The present is a decisive threshold for finite existence. It is the threshold where past and future meet and can give birth to a livable horizon of meaning. Dilating the present and giving it a meaningful chance to be is a task for philosophy. It is the attempt of giving time to time and also giving it shape, place, and space. To succeed at this task while rediscovering the sources of a narrative way of thinking that in truth it has never abandoned, philosophy must go back and turn time into the primary object of discourse, like in stories, which are precisely the attempt at disposing the temporal flow of events according to a meaning. Perone argues that in time, however, what passes is not simply decline, but rather something irreducible, an exteriority that must be said.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Hermeneutics. 4aPhilosophy : Phenomenology. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Religion. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh1 aBenso, Silvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchroeder, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781438437477?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438437477423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438437477/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles